\section{Introduction}

Functional logic programming has a long history and a rich literature.
But it is somewhat tricky for programmers to reason about functional logic programs: they must think about
logical variables, narrowing, backtracking, Horn clauses, resolution,
and the like.   This contrasts with functional programming,
where one can say ``just apply rewrite rules, such as beta reduction, let-inlining, and case-of-known-constructor''.
Moreover, these rewrite rules apply even in the presence of free variables; that is, under lambdas.

We therefore seek a completely-precise expression of functional logic programming, as
at term rewriting system, to give us both a formal semantics (via a small-step reductions),
and a powerful set of equvalences that programmers can use to reason about their programs,
and compilers can use to optimise them.

Our main contribution is a new core calculus, the Verse calculus or \versecalc{} for short,
for functional logic programming that
has the following properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item It natively supports \emph{higher-order programming}, just like the lambda calculus.  In contrast,
  the functional-logic literature typically addresses higher order features via defunctionalisation \cite[3.3]{hanus:survey}.
\item It supports \emph{logical variables}. In the expression |def x e|, the variable |x| is brought into scope,
  but gains its value through \emph{equalities} |(e_1 = e_2)| in |e|.  Like any declarative language, however,
  an existential variable always stands for a single value; logical variables are not mutable.
\item It supports so-called \emph{non-deterministic programming}; that is, an expression can return one result, many results, or no result (failure).
  As a result, it natively supports both narrowing and residuation.
\item \versecalc{} has a \emph{small-step term rewriting semantics} (\Cref{sec:rewrite-rules}).
  Just like rewriting for the lambda calculus, this semantics allows programmers to reason, step by step,
  about how their program executes.  This set of rewrite rules is our main contribution.
\item \simon{Something about confluence.}
\end{itemize}
As always with a calculus, the idea is that \versecalc{} distils the essence of functional logic programming.
Each construct does just one thing, and \versecalc{} cannot be made smaller without losing key features.
It should be possible to compile a variety of functional logic languages,
including Curry \cite{hanus:curry-report}, into \versecalc{}.
We are also working on Verse, a new programming language for the metaverse, built directly on \versecalc{}; indeed,
our motivation for developing \versecalc{} is practical rather than theoretical.

There is a rich seam of related work; an excellent starting point is Hanus's survey \cite{hanus:survey}.
We discuss related work in \cref{sec:related}.

