\subsection{Pattern matching and narrowing}

We remarked in \Cref{sec:unify} that we can desugar the pattern matching of a high-level
languag into unification. But what about pattern matching with multiple equations, such as this definition in Haskell:
\begin{code}
  append []      ys = ys
  append (x:xs)  ys = x : append xs ys
\end{code}
If pattern matching on the first equation fails, we want to fall through to the second.
Fortunately, choice allows us to express this idea directly\footnote{
We use the empty tuple |emptytup| to represent the empty list and pairs to represent |cons|;
and we allow ourselves to write |lamhdr (tup(x,y)) body| rather than |lam p (def (x,y) (p = tup (x,y); body)|
  }:
$$
|append =lamhdr (tup (xs,ys))| \begin{array}[t]{l}
  |(xs = emptytup; ys) choice| \\
  |(def (a,as) (xs = tup (a,as); tup (a, applyN append (as, ys))))|
\end{array}
$$
If |xs| is |emptytup|, the left hand choice succeeds, returning |y|; and the right hand choice
fails (by attempting to unify |emptytup| with |tup(a,as)|).
If |xs| is of form |tup (y,ys)|,
the right hand choice succeeds, and we make a recursive call to |append|.
Finally if |xs| is built with head normal forms other than the empty tuple and pairs, both choices fail, and |append| returns no
results.

This approach to pattern matching is akin to \emph{narrowing} \cite{hanus:survey}.
Suppose |single = tup (1, emptytup)|, a singleton list whose only element is 1.
Consider this call:
$$
|def xs (applyN append ( xs, single) = single; xs)|
$$
The call to |append| expands into a choice
$$
  |(xs = emptytup; single)| \quad |choice| \quad
  |(def (a,as) (xs = tup (a,as); tup(a, applyN append (as, single))))|
$$
which amounts to exploring the possiblity that |xs| is headed by |emptytup| or a pair -- the
essence of narrowing.  It should not take long to reassure yourself that the program
evaluates to |emptytup|, effectively running |append| backwards in the classic logic-programming manner.

This example also illustrates that \versecalc{} allows an equality (for |append|)
that is recursive. As in any functional langauge with recursive bindings, you can
go into an infinite loop if you keep fruitlessly inlining the function in its own right hand side.
It is the busines of an \emph{evaluation} strategy to do only rewrites that make
progress towards a solution.

\subsection{Conditionals and |oneKW|} \label{sec:rigid} \label{sec:one} \label{sec:if}

Every source language will provide a conditional, like |if (x=0) then
e_2 else e_3|.  But what is the equality operator in |(x=0)|?  One
possiblity, adopted by Curry, is this: there is one ``='' for
equations (as in \cref{sec:unify}), and another, say ``=='', for
testing equality (returning a boolean with constructors |True| and |False|).  \versecalc{} takes a
different, more minimalist position. In \versecalc{} \emph{there is just one equality operator}, written ``='' just as in
\cref{sec:unify}. The expression |if (x=0) then e_2 else e_3| tries to unify |x| with |0|.  If that succeeds (returns one or more values)
the |if| returns |e_2|; otherwise it returns |e_3|.  There are no data constructors |True| and |False|; instead
failure plays the role of falsity.

But something is terribly wrong here.  Consider |def (x,y) (y = (if (x=0) 3 4); x=7)|.  Presumably this is meant
to set |x| to |7|, test if it is equal to |0| (it is not), and unify |y| with 4.
But what is to stop us instead unifying |x| with |0| (via |(x=0)|), unifying |y| with |3|, and then
failing when we try to unify |x| with |7|?  Not only is that not what we intended, but it also looks very
non-deterministic: the result is affected by the order in which we did unifications!

To address this, we give |if| a special property: in the expression |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3|, unifications inside |e_1| (the condition of the |if|)
can only unify variables |defKW|'d inside |e_1|; variables bound outside |e_1| are ``rigid''.  So in our example, the |x| in |(x=0)| is
rigid and cannot be unified.  Instead the |if| is stuck, and we move on to unify |x=7|.  That unblocks
the |if| and all is well.  This special property is precisely the local propagation rule that we sketched for
choice (\cref{sec:mixing}).

In fact, \versecalc{} distills the three-argument |if| into something simpler, the unary construct |one(e)|.
Its specification is this:
if |e| fails, |one(e)| fails; otherwise |one(e)| returns the first of the values yielded by |e|.
Now, |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3| can (nearly) be re-expressed like this:
$$
|one( (e_1; e_2) choice e_3 )|
$$
If |e_1| fails, the first branch of the choice fails, so we get |e_3|; if |e_1| succeeds, we
get |e_2|, and the outer |oneKW| will select it from the choice.  But this isn't right:
what if |e_2| or |e_3| themselves fail or return multiple results?  Here is a better translation,
which wraps the then and else branches in a thunk:
$$
|apply0 (one( (e_1; (thunk (e_2))) choice (thunk (e_3))))|
$$
The argument of |oneKW| evaluates to either |((thunk (e_2)) choice dots)| or |(thunk (e_3))|
depending on whether |e_1| succeeds or fails, respectively, and |oneKW| then picks that lambda and applies it to |emptytup|.
As a bonus, provided we do no evaluation under a lambda, then |e_2| and |e_3| will
remain un-evaluated until the choice is made, just as we expect.

We use the same local-propagation rule for |oneKW| that we do for choice (\Cref{sec:mixing});
together with the desugaring for |if| into |oneKW|,
we get the ``special property'' of |if| described above.

\subsection{Arrays and |allKW|} \label{sec:array}
The main data structure in \versecalc{} is the array.
An array is a finite sequence of values, |tup (v_1,dots,v_n)|.
It can be used like a function: indexing is simply function application
with the argument being integers from 0 and up.  Indexing out of range is |fail|.
For example, |def a (a = (10,27,32); apply1 a 1)| reduces to |27|.
The reduction rule for indexing in arrays allows a multi-valued index expression.
For instance, |a := (10,27,32); apply1 a (1 `choice` 0 `choice` 1)| will reduce to |(27 `choice` 10 `choice` 27)|.

Arrays can be constructed by collecting all the results from a multi-valued expression, using the |allKW| construct:
if |e| fails the |all e| is the empty array,
otherwise if |e| reduces to |(v_1 `choice` dots `choice` v_n)| then |all e| reduces to
the array |tup (v_1, dots, v_n)|.
\lennart{Somewhere we should mention that |choice| is associative (in some sense) and can be reassociated.}
\label{sec:all}

You might think that array indexing would be stuck until we know the index,
but \versecalc{} uses narrowing to make progress. The expression |(def i (apply1 a i))|
looks stuck because we have no value for |i|, but in fact it rewrites to
$$
|def i ((i=0; 10) choice (i=1; 27) choice (i=2; 32)|
$$
which (as we will see in \Cref{sec:rewrite-rules}) simplifies
to just |(10 `choice` 27 `choice` 32)|.
So |allKW| allows a choice to be reified into an array; and |(def i (apply1 a i))| allow an
array to be turned back into a choice.

Do we even need |oneKW| as a primitive construct, given that we have
|allKW|? Can we not use |apply1 (all e) 0| instead of |one e|? Indeed
they behave the same if |e| fully reduces to finitely many choices of
values. But |allKW| really requires the evaluation of \emph{all}
choices before proceeding, while |oneKW| only needs to evaluate the
first choice. So, supposing that |loop| is a non-terminating function,
|one (1 `choice` apply0 loop)| reduces to 1, while
|apply1 (all (1 `choice` apply0 loop)) 0| loops.


