\section{Some Verse examples} \label{sec:verse}
\versecalc{} is a fairly small language, but it is quite expressive.
We will illustrate this with a few examples.

\subsection{Syntactic sugar}

\begin{figure}
  $$
  \begin{array}{l}
    \begin{array}{rcll}
      |x := e; dots| & \equiv & |def x (x = e; dots)| \\
      |apply1 f x := e; dots| & \equiv & |f := lam x e; dots| \\
      |applyN f (x,y) := e; dots| & \equiv & |apply1 f p := (def (x,y) (p=tup (x,y); e)); dots| & \text{|p| fresh} \\
      |apply1 e_1 e_2| & \equiv & |def (x,y) (x = e_1;y=e_2;apply1 x y)| & \text{|x,y| fresh} \\
      |tup (e_1, e_2)| & \equiv & |def (x,y) (x = e_1;y=e_2; tup (x,y))| & \text{|x,y| fresh} \\
      |e_1+e_2| & \equiv & |applyN add (e_1,e_2)| \\
      |e_1>e_2| & \equiv & |applyN gt (e_1,e_2)| \\
      |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3| & \equiv & |t := one( (e_1; thunk e_2) choice (thunk e_3)); apply0 t| & \text{|t,x| fresh} \\
      |for e_1 in e_2| & \equiv & |v := all (e_1; thunk e_2); apply1 map (tup (lam z (apply0 z), v)| & \text{|v,x| fresh} \\
    \end{array} \\
  \end{array}
  $$
\caption{Syntactic sugar}
\label{fig:sugar}
\end{figure}

The {\versecalc} grammar can be a bit unwieldy, with explicit |defKW| and ANF-like restrictions allowing only values,
not arbitrary expressions, in in array literals and function-applications.
To keep the examples readable, we allow ourselves a bit of syntactic sugar, summarized in \cref{fig:sugar}:
\begin{itemize}
\item With |:=| we simultaneously introduce and assign a variable.
\item When defining functions, we allow simple patterns on the left of |:=|
\item In function applications we allow ourselves to write |apply1 e_1 e_2|,
  rather that insisting on both function and argument being a value, and
  likewise for pairs |tup (e_1,e_2)|.
\item We allow the use of |if|, as explained in \cref{sec:if}.
\item We allow the use of |for|, as we will explain in \cref{sec:for}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}
  $$
  \begin{array}{l}
    \begin{array}{l@@{\;}l}
      |apply1 head xs| & :=  |one (def i (apply1 xs i))| \\
      |apply1 tail xs| & :=  |all (def i (i > 0; apply1 xs i))| \\
      |applyN cons (x,xs)| & :=  |all (x `choice` def i (apply1 xs i))| \\
      |applyN append (xs, ys)| & :=  |all (def i (apply1 xs i) `choice` def i (apply1 ys i))| \\
      |applyN flatMap (f,xs)| & := |all (def i (apply1 f (apply1 xs i)))| \\
      |applyN map (f, xs)| & :=  |if x := apply1 head xs then applyN cons (apply1 f x, applyN map (f,apply1 tail xs)) else emptytup| \\
      |applyN filter (p, xs)| & :=  |all (def i (x := apply1 xs i; one (apply1 p x); x)))| \\
      |applyN find (p, xs)| & :=  |one (def i (x := apply1 xs i; one (apply1 p x); x)))| \\
      |applyN every (p, xs)| & :=  |applyN map (p,xs)| \\
    \end{array}
  \end{array}
  $$
\caption{Common list functions} \label{fig:list-functions}
\end{figure}

\subsection{List functions}

We can define the typical list functions one would expect from functional programming
by using the duality between arrays and choices, as seen in \cref{fig:list-functions}.
An array can be turned into choices by indexing, |apply1 a i|, with a logical variable |i|.
Conversely, choices can be turned into an array using |allKW|.
The choice operator, |choice|, serves as both |cons| and |append| for choices
and |oneKW| is like |head| for choices.  With that in mind, here is how to understand
the definitions in \cref{fig:list-functions}:
\begin{itemize}
\item |head|.
To obtain the first element of an array, we turn the array into a sequence of choices and then pick out the first value using |oneKW|. If the array is empty, |head| fails.

\item |tail|.
To get the tail of an array, again we apply the array to a fresh variable, and restrict that variable with |i > 0|.
This way, the expression fails at the first value and only the other values are collected by |allKW|.
This definition of |tail| returns the empty array if |xs| is empty or not even an array.

\item |cons| and |append|.
We can implement |applyN cons (x,xs)| by collecting with |allKW| the choices we get from choosing |x|,
or all the elements of |xs|, and similarly we can define |append|.

\item |flatMap|.
For the function |map|, which applies a function to each element of an array and collects the results,
two possible implementation come to mind, and they differ when the function passed to |map| fails or produces more than a single value.
|flatMap| flattens the choices from iterating through |xs| with
the choices taken by |f|, so |applyN flatMap ( (lam x ((x choice x+1))), tup (10,20)))| $\equiv$ |tup (10,11,20,21)|.

\item |map|.
But often this is not what we want: we may want the effects of |f|, such as failure or returning multiple values,
to affect the whole expression and obtain the cartesian product of these choices.
The expression |applyN map ((lam x ((x `choice` x+1))), tup (10,20))| should reduce to |tup (10,20)`choice` tup(10,21) `choice` tup (11,20) `choice` tup (11,21)|.
We get that behaviour if we simply define |map| much like in any other functional programming language:
if taking the head of the array fails, it must be an empty array, and we return an empty array.
Else we apply |f| to the head, recurse on the |tail| and assemble the result with |cons|.\label{sec:map}

\item |filter|.
How can we filter an array with a predicate |p|?
We turn the array into the sequence of choices, and let those fail where |p| fails before collecting the other values into an array.

\item |find|.
If we use |oneKW| instead of |allKW|, we get the function that checks if |p| holds for some element of the array,
and returns the first matching element, or fails if |p| does not hold for any element.

\item |every|.
And to test if a predicate |p| holds for every element of an array |xs|, we can simply use |map(p,xs)|!
If |p| fails for any value, the whole call to |map(p,xs)| fails.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Choice comprehensions} \label{sec:for}

Source languages can use this to build more featureful constructs like |for|,
mimicking the list comprehension in languages like Haskell or Python:
The expression |for^(e_1) in e_2| will evaluate |e_2| for each of the choices in |e_1|.
The |e_1| is called the \emph{domain} of the loop.

The scoping is peculiar in that variables bound in |e_1| also scope over |e_2|.
So, e.g., |for^(def x (x = 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5)) in (x+1)| will reduce to the array |tup (3,4,6)|.
This example can, with the |:=| shorthand, be written |for^(x := 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5) in (x+1)|.

Like list comprehension it supports filtering, but in Verse this falls out naturally by just using
a possibly failing expression in the domain.
So, |for^(x := 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5; x > 2) in (x+1)| reduces to the array |tup (4,6)|.

Nested iteration in a |for| works as expected, and requires nothing special.
So, |for^(x:=10 `choice` 20; y := 1 `choice` 2 `choice` 3) in x+y| reduces to |tup (11, 12, 13, 21, 22, 23)|

Just like |if| is defined in terms of the primitive |oneKW| we can define |for|
in terms of the primitive |all e|.
Again, we have to be careful when |e_2| itself fails or produces multiple results;
simply writing |all (e1;e2)| would give the wrong semantics. So we put |e_2| under a lambda, and
apply each element of the array to |emptytup| afterwards, using the |map| function defined above.
The full desugaring for |for^(e_1) in e_2| is thus
\[
|v := all (e_1; thunk e_2); applyN map ((lam z (apply0 z)), v)|
\]
for a fresh variable |v|.

Note how this achieves that peculiar scoping rule: variables defined in |e_1| are in scope in |e_2|.
Any effects (like being multivalued) in |e_2| will not affect the choices defined by |e_1| since they are in a thunk.
So, e.g., |for^(x:=1 `choice` 2) in {3 `choice` x}| will reduce to
|tup (3, 3) `choice` tup (3, 2) `choice` tup (1, 3) `choice` tup (1, 2)|.
At this point it is crucial to use |map|, not |mapFlat|.

Given that array indexing expands into choices, we can iterate over array indices and elements using |for|.
E.g., |for^(def (i, x) (x = apply1 a i)) in x+i| will produce an array with the elements of |a|, increased by their index in |a|.


\subsection{Enumerations}
Making a choice between a sequence of numbers can be expressed like this
$$
\begin{array}{lll}
  |applyN fromTo (lo,hi)| & := & |if lo > hi then fail else lo `choice` applyN fromTo (lo+1,hi)|
\end{array}
$$
so |for^(x:= applyN fromTo (1,5)) in x| will reduce to the array |tup (1,2,3,4,5)|.

\subsection{Handling out-of-bounds errors}
Indexing out-of-bounds of an array results in |fail|.
This means that we cannot avoid handling this case.
$$
|if x:=apply1 a 5 then apply1 print x else apply1 print "out of bounds"|
$$

\subsection{Subset and powerset}
\lennart{Is this example too elementary?}
The subsets (subarrays) of of an array can be expressed with this multi-valued function.
First compute the subsets of all but the first element, and then return these with and without the first element added.
$$
|subset^(a) := if x:=apply1 head a then s:= apply1 subset (apply1 tail a); applyN cons (x, s) `choice` s else emptytup|
$$
And computing the powerset is then simply a matter of collecting all the subsets into an array.
$$
|powerset^(a) := for x := apply1 subset a in x|
$$

