\subsection{Not restricting application and arrays}

We have opted to restrict array formation and function application to only allow \emph{values} and not \emph{expressions}.
This is not a necessary restriction, but allowing expressions would require many more rules.
The extra rules would describe how to distribute, e.g., application over sequencing.
There is no loss of expressive power using just values, just slightly more verbose terms.

\subsection{Restricting unification}

The system becomes slightly simpler if we restrict the syntax of equalities so that the left-hand-side is always a value.
Thus $e ::= \ldots \vb |v = e| \vb \ldots$. It is easy to get the program into this form:
$$
|e_1 = e_2| \quad \text{desugars to} \quad |def x (x = e_1; x = e_2)|
$$
The payoff is that we can then drop \rulename{unify-seql} and \rulename{unify-unifyl}.
The difference is modest, but it would make our language a little smaller.

\subsection{Ordering and choices}

As we discussed in \cref{sec:choice-rules}, rule \rulename{choose} is less than satisfying, for two reasons.
First, the |CX| context uses a conservative, syntactic analysis for choice-free expressions; and second,
the |SX| context is needed to force |CX| to be maximal.  A rule like this would be more satisfying:
$$
\rulename{simpler-choose} \quad   |X^[ e_1 choice e_2 ]| \movesto |X^[e_1] choice X^[e_2]|
$$
The trouble with that is that it may change the order of the results (\cref{sec:mixing}).
Another possiblity would be to accept the the results may come out in the ``wrong'' order, but have
some kind of sorting mechanism to put them back into the ``right'' order.  Something like this:
$$
\rulename{labelled-choose} \quad   |X^[ e_1 choice e_2 ]| \movesto |X^[L; e_1] choice X^[R; e_2]|
$$
Here the two branches are labelled with |L| and |R|.  We can add new rules to reorder such
labelled expressions, something like
$$
\rulename{sort-l} \quad   |(R; e_1) choice (L; e_2)| \movesto |(L; e_2) choice (R; e_1)|
$$
We believe this can be made to work, but it adds unwelcome clutter to program terms, and the cure
may be worse than the disease.

\subsection{Generalizing |oneKW| and |allKW|}

In \versecalc{} we introduced |oneKW| and |allKW| as the primitive choice-consuming operators, and neither is more general than the other, as discussed in \cref{sec:all}. We could have, however, introduced a more general operator |splitKW| as $e ::=  |dots| \vb |split e v_1 v_2|$ and rules
\[\begin{array}{lrcll}
    \rulename{split-fail} & |split fail f g| & \movesto & |apply0 f| \\
    \rulename{split-choice} & |split (v `choice` e) f g| & \movesto & |applyN g (v, thunk e)| & \text{|x| fresh}  \\
    \rulename{split-value} & |split v f g| & \movesto & |applyN g (v, thunk fail)| \\
\end{array}\]
The intuition behind |splitKW| is that it distinguishes a failing computation from one that returns at least one value. If |e| fails, it calls |f|, and if |e| returns at least one value, passes that to |g| together with the remaining computation, safely tucked away behind a lambda.

Indeed, this is more general, as we can implement |oneKW| and |allKW| with |splitKW|:
\[\begin{array}{r@@{\;}l@@{\;}l@@{\;}l}
    |one e| & \equiv |apply1 f x := fail; | & |applyN g (x,y):= x;| & |split e f g| \\
    |all e| & \equiv |apply1 f x := emptytup;|    & |applyN g (x,y):= applyN cons (x, split (apply0 y) f g);| & |split e f g|
\end{array}\]
For this paper we stuck to the arguably simpler |oneKW| and |allKW|,
to avoid confusing the presentation with these higher-order encoding, but we do not expect any complications using |splitKW| instead.



\section{Conclusions and further work}
\lennart{This needs a little fleshing out.}

\subsection{Types}
The full Verse language has types and static checking of those.
In the dynamic semantics the types can be represented by partial
identity function---identity of the values of the type and |fail| otherwise.
We have a reduction rules for this, but they are left out for space and exposition reasons.

\subsection{Assignment}
The full Verse language has updateable references in a store, in the style of SML.
We also have (tentative) reduction rules for this as well.
They are non-trivial, because store updates have to be transactions, e.g.,
when the condition of an |if| fails any store effects in the condition are rolled back.
See \cref{sec:store} for the relevant rules.

\subsection{Effects}
In this paper we have seen one kind of effect, namely being multi-valued.
Adding assignable references add another set of effects, as does I/O.
To accomodate this, real Verse has an effect system in addition to the type system.
We have reduction rules for effect checking as well, but for the real language this is done at compile time.

